    "title": "Enhanced Reliability Vaccine Delivery Box",
    "subtitle": "A dual-Peltier, RFID-locked cold box engineered to hold Jordan's vaccines at 2–8°C through 43°C summers, with a full auditable temperature trail.",
    "category": "Engineering",
    "year": "2026",
    "description": "A smart vaccine cold box built for Jordan's last-mile healthcare delivery, combining active dual-Peltier cooling with a copper heat-pipe loop, a passive PCM thermal buffer, and a supercapacitor emergency backup into three independent layers of temperature protection. An RFID-based locking system authenticates every access event and automatically fail-locks if the box excursions outside the safe 2–8°C range, while an onboard microcontroller logs temperature, battery voltage, and access data every 5 minutes for 30 days. Designed to WHO's 43°C performance standard and aligned with JFDA, UNICEF E004, and EU Ecodesign requirements, the full prototype was built for roughly 118 JOD in materials. Developed for HTU's Engineering Project Management course.",
    "longDescription": "The Problem\n\nVaccine cold chains break down at the last mile. Roughly 35% of vaccines worldwide experience temperature excursions in transport, driving potency losses of up to 15% and roughly $35 billion in annual global losses. In Jordan specifically, summer ambient temperatures regularly exceed 43°C, immunization tracking is still largely paper-based, and cold chain infrastructure ages faster than it gets replaced. The Enhanced Reliability Vaccine Delivery Box (VDB) was built to close that specific gap: keep vaccines inside the WHO-mandated 2–8°C band, make every excursion undeniable and logged, and do it all at a materials cost realistic for Jordan's healthcare system.\n\nSystem Architecture — Three-Layer Thermal Defense\n\n1. Active cooling — dual Peltier + copper heat-pipe loop.\nTwo TEC1-12706 thermoelectric modules (40×40×3.6mm, 12V/6A, 72W max each) are wired in parallel, giving redundancy if one module fails. Rather than cooling a single point, each Peltier's cold face bonds via thermal paste to a copper cold block, which feeds 3–4 sintered-wick copper heat pipes running along the compartment's interior walls and floor. These are sealed, passive two-phase devices — water evaporates at the interior end, carries heat as vapor to the cold block, condenses, and wicks back with no pump and no moving parts — spreading cold evenly across the whole interior rather than one cold plate. The Peltier hot faces vent through external aluminum heat sinks with 12V fans, and a microcontroller uses MOSFET-based PWM to regulate both modules independently, capping the achievable ΔT at roughly 66°C — comfortably enough to hold 5°C against a 43°C ambient.\n\n2. Passive buffer — Phase Change Material (PCM).\nTwo water-based PCM packs sit in the lid, pre-frozen for a minimum of 12 hours (14+ in extreme heat) before deployment. Their job isn't primary cooling — that's the Peltier system's — but reducing Peltier duty cycle in normal operation, absorbing heat spikes when the lid opens, and maintaining sub-8°C conditions passively during a power failure. Because PCM releases cold through a phase transition at a near-constant rate rather than a temperature gradient, it can't over-cool vaccines below 2°C the way an ice pack could, as long as vaccines stay off the packs directly (foam holders buffer this).\n\n3. Emergency backup — supercapacitor.\nIf primary battery voltage drops below threshold, a supercapacitor kicks in automatically, self-recharging during normal operation and providing 15–30 minutes of runtime — enough to reach a facility or transfer vaccines to alternate cold storage, not a substitute for a charged battery.\n\nInsulation. An HDPE outer shell (410× lower thermal conductivity than aluminum, impact-resistant) wraps a polyurethane spray-foam core, sealed by a multi-layer silicone gasket, with shock-absorbing interior foam holding vaccines and buffering them from the PCM packs.\n\nSmart RFID Locking\n\nAn RC522 reader (13.56 MHz, ISO 14443A, up to 10 registered operator profiles) governs access. A normal unlock is a single tap: the MCU authenticates the card, checks temperature status, and releases both latches simultaneously with an audible beep — the lid must open within 10 seconds or it re-locks automatically. Every access event (card UID, timestamp, interior temperature) is logged. The safety-critical feature is the excursion fail-safe: if interior temperature sits outside 2–8°C for more than 5 continuous minutes, the Red LED activates, the RFID system enters DENY mode, and the lock can only be cleared by a supervisor's Master RFID card plus the USB software — preventing anyone from delivering vaccines that may already be compromised.\n\nStatus & Monitoring\n\nA three-LED traffic light gives field operators an at-a-glance read: Green (2–8°C, all clear), Amber (approaching the limit, Peltier PWM maxed, monitor every 5 minutes), Red (excursion, box locked, stop and call supervisor), and Flashing (battery failed, supercapacitor active, get power now). Two DS18B20 sensors (±0.5°C) feed the onboard Arduino/ESP32-compatible microcontroller, which logs temperature, battery voltage, and RFID events every 5 minutes to non-volatile memory — persisting even if the battery is removed — with 30 days of storage. Logs download over USB as CSV, or export as PDF for JFDA regulatory submissions, and Jordan's rules require records to be retained 5 years and made available for inspection within 24 hours of request.\n\nCompliance by Design\n\nThe VDB was engineered against multiple standards simultaneously rather than one: WHO Performance Qualification (43°C and −20°C thermal testing, 2–8°C internal range), UNICEF Supply Division's E004 cold-box specification for EPI procurement, JFDA's Drug and Pharmacy Law No. 80 of 2001 (auditable per-trip temperature records), EU Ecodesign Regulation 2019/2022 (addressed via the smart Li-Ion + supercapacitor power design), and both NSPE and IEEE codes of ethics — the latter driving decisions like choosing HDPE over aluminum for public safety and documenting design weaknesses openly rather than hiding them.\n\nBill of Materials & Cost\n\nThe full prototype's materials cost totals 117.60 JOD, spanning four subsystems: cooling (Peltier modules, heat pipes, heat sinks/fans, thermal paste, PCM packs), housing/insulation (HDPE shell, spray foam, shock-absorbing foam, silicone gasket, hardware), electronics/sensors (RFID module, Thermocouple sensors, Esp32, status Buzzers, solenoid latches, wiring), and power management (BMS, step-up converters, supercapacitor, Li-PO Battery) — nearly all sourced locally in Jordan. ",
